files.Summary:
In the context of ISO 19115, is an abstract class representing a structured identifier or name in a namespace. It is a conceptual construct; a placeholder for specific name types which represents a textual 'name' in geospatial metadata. It is commonly used to define hierarchical naming conventions, such as:

  • feature types

In GML, a 'name' is commonly modeled as a GML , which can carry a string and an optional codeSpace attribute. The typically ties into this pattern.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.AbstractMemberType
files.Summary: To create a collection of GML Objects that are not all features, a property type shall be derived by extension from . This abstract property type is intended to be used only in object types where software shall be able to identify that an instance of such an object type is to be interpreted as a collection of objects. By default, this abstract property type does not imply any ownership of the objects in the collection. The owns attribute of gml:OwnershipAttributeGroup may be used on a property element instance to assert ownership of an object in the collection. files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.AbstractMetadataPropertyType
files.Summary:
To associate metadata described by any XML Schema with a GML object, a property element shall be defined whose content model is derived by extension from . The value of such a property shall be metadata. The content model of such a property type, i.e. the metadata application schema shall be specified by the GML Application Schema. By default, this abstract property type does not imply any ownership of the metadata. The property (owns attribute) of the (gml:OwnershipAttributeGroup) may be used on a metadata property element instance to assert ownership of the metadata.

If metadata following the conceptual model of ISO 19115 is to be encoded in a GML document, the corresponding Implementation Specification specified in ISO/TS 19139 shall be used to encode the metadata information.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.AssociationAndOwnership
files.Summary:
Represents a generalized association in GML, providing an XLink-based mechanism for referencing external or internal resources within geospatial metadata. This abstract class implements the GML AssociationAttributeGroup pattern from gmlBase.xsd, enabling a standard approach for linking GML objects and facilitating interoperability with ISO 19115:2003 metadata structures.

Encoding a GML property in-line vs by-reference shall not imply anything about the “ownership” of the contained or referenced GML Object, i.e. the encoding style shall not imply any “deep-copy” or “deep-delete” semantics.To express ownership over the contained or referenced GML Object, the gml:OwnershipAttributeGroup attribute group may be added to object-valued property elements.If the attribute group is not part of the content model of such a property element, then the value may not be “owned”. When the value of the owns attribute is true, the existence of in-line or referenced object(s) depends upon the existence of the parent object.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.BasicTypes.CoordinatesType
files.Summary:
The is deprecated for tuples with ordinate values that are numbers. The is a text string, intended to be used to record an array of tuples or coordinates. While it is not possible to enforce the internal structure of the string through schema validation, some optional attributes have been provided in previous versions of GML to support a description of the internal structure. These attributes are deprecated. The attributes were intended to be used as follows:

  • Decimal symbolUsed for a decimal point (default="." a stop or period).
  • cs symbol Used to separate components within a tuple or coordinate string (default="," a comma).
  • ts symbol Used to separate tuples or coordinate strings (default=" " a space).

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coordinate.Datums.EngineeringDatumType

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coordinate.Datums.GeodeticDatumType

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coordinate.Datums.ImageDatumType

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coordinate.Datums.SecondDefiningParameter
files.Summary:
The is a property containing the definition of the second parameter that defines the shape of an ellipsoid. An ellipsoid requires two defining parameters:

  1. Semi-major axis and Inverse flattening
  2. Semi-major axis and Semi-minor axis
When the reference body is a sphere rather than an , only a single defining parameter is required, namely the radius of the sphere; in that case, the semi-major axis "degenerates" into the radius of the sphere.

The inverseFlattening element contains the inverse flattening value of the . This value is a scale factor (or ratio). It uses gml:LengthType with the restriction that the unit of measure referenced by the uom attribute must be suitable for a scale factor, such as percent, permil, or parts-per-million.

The semiMinorAxis element contains the length of the semi-minor axis of the ellipsoid. When the isSphere element is included, the ellipsoid is degenerate and is actually a sphere. The sphere is completely defined by the semi-major axis, which is the radius of the sphere.

Maps to: SecondDefiningParameter ( /2005/gml/datums.xsd )

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coordinate.Operations.ConcatenatedOperationType
files.Summary: gml:ConcatenatedOperation is an ordered sequence of two or more coordinate operations. This sequence of operations is constrained by the requirement that the source coordinate reference system of step (n+1) must be the same as the target coordinate reference system of step (n). The source coordinate reference system of the first step and the target coordinate reference system of the last step are the source and target coordinate reference system associated with the concatenated operation. Instead of a forward operation, an inverse operation may be used for one or more of the operation steps mentioned above, if the inverse operation is uniquely defined by the forward operation. The gml:coordOperation property elements are an ordered sequence of associations to the two or more operations used by this concatenated operation. The AggregationAttributeGroup should be used to specify that the coordOperation associations are ordered.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coordinate.Operations.ConversionPropertyType

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coordinate.Operations.CoordinateOperationAccuracy

That object contains an estimate of the impact of this coordinate operation on point accuracy. That is, it gives position error estimates for the target coordinates of this coordinate operation, assuming no errors in the source coordinates.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coordinate.Operations.GeneralConversionPropertyType
files.Summary: gml:GeneralConversionPropertyType is a property type for association roles to a general conversion, either referencing or containing the definition of that conversion.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coordinate.Operations.GeneralTransformationPropertyType
files.Summary: gml:GeneralTransformationPropertyType is a property type for association roles to a general transformation, either referencing or containing the definition of that transformation.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coordinate.Operations.OperationMethodPropertyType
files.Summary: gml:OperationMethodPropertyType is a property type for association roles to a concrete general-purpose operation method, either referencing or containing the definition of that method.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coordinate.Operations.OperationParameterGroupPropertyType
files.Summary: gml:OperationParameterPropertyType is a property type for association roles to an operation parameter group, either referencing or containing the definition of that parameter group.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coordinate.Operations.OperationParameterPropertyType
files.Summary: gml:OperationParameterPropertyType is a property type for association roles to an operation parameter, either referencing or containing the definition of that parameter.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coordinate.Operations.PassThroughOperationPropertyType
files.Summary: gml:PassThroughOperationPropertyType is a property type for association roles to a pass through operation, either referencing or containing the definition of that pass through operation.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coordinate.Operations.PassThroughOperationType
files.Summary: gml:PassThroughOperation is a pass-through operation specifies that a subset of a coordinate tuple is subject to a specific coordinate operation. The modifiedCoordinate property elements are an ordered sequence of positive integers defining the positions in a coordinate tuple of the coordinates affected by this pass-through operation. The AggregationAttributeGroup should be used to specify that the modifiedCoordinate elements are ordered.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coordinate.Operations.SingleOperationPropertyType
files.Summary: gml:SingleOperationPropertyType is a property type for association roles to a single operation, either referencing or containing the definition of that single operation.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coordinate.Operations.TransformationType
files.Summary:
The is a concrete object element derived from (13.6.2.13).

This concrete object can be used for all operation methods, without using a GML Application Schema that defines operation-method-specialized element names and contents, especially for methods with only one Transformation instance. The parameterValue elements are an unordered list of composition associations to the set of parameter values used by this conversion operation.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coordinate.ReferenceSystems.AbstractGeneralDerivedCRSType
files.Summary: The is a coordinate reference system that is defined by its coordinate conversion from another coordinate reference system. This abstract complex type shall not be used, extended, or restricted, in a GML Application Schema, to define a concrete subtype with a meaning equivalent to a concrete subtype specified in this document.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coordinate.ReferenceSystems.AbstractSingleCRS
files.Summary: The implements a coordinate reference system consisting of one coordinate system and one datum (as opposed to a Compound CRS).

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coordinate.ReferenceSystems.CompoundCRSType
files.Summary: The is a coordinate reference system that describes the position of points through two or more independent coordinate reference systems. It is associated with a non-repeating sequence of two or more instances of single coordinate reference systems, typically concrete classes that inherit from and implement the interface.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coordinate.ReferenceSystems.DerivedCRSType
files.Summary: The is a single coordinate reference system that is defined by its coordinate conversion from another single coordinate reference system known as the base CRS. The base CRS can be a projected coordinate reference system, if this is used for a geo-rectified grid coverage as described in ISO 19123, Clause 8.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coordinate.ReferenceSystems.EngineeringCRSType
files.Summary:
The is a contextually local coordinate reference system which can be divided into two broad categories:

  • Earth-fixed SystemsThey are applied to engineering activities on or near the surface of the earth
  • CRSs on moving platforms

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coordinate.ReferenceSystems.GeocentricCRSType
files.Summary: The is defined by a geodetic datum and using either a or .

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coordinate.ReferenceSystems.GeodeticCRSType
files.Summary: The is a coordinate reference system based on a geodetic datum.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coordinate.ReferenceSystems.GeographicCRSType
files.Summary: The uses an ellipsoidal coordinate system and is associated with a geodetic datum. A defines positions on or near the Earth's surface using angular coordinates such as latitude and longitude.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coordinate.ReferenceSystems.IProjectedCoordinateReferenceSystem
files.Summary: The represents a two-dimensional coordinate reference system derived from a geodetic or geographic base coordinate reference system CRS by applying a map projection.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coordinate.ReferenceSystems.ISingleCRS
files.Summary: The is used to mark coordinate reference system objects consisting of one coordinate system and one datum (as opposed to a Compound CRS).

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coordinate.ReferenceSystems.ImageCRSType
files.Summary: The is an engineering coordinate reference system applied to locations in images. Image coordinate reference systems are treated as a separate sub-type because the definition of the associated image datum contains two attributes not relevant to other engineering datums.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coordinate.ReferenceSystems.ProjectedCRSType
files.Summary: The is a 2D coordinate reference system used to approximate the shape of the earth on a planar surface, but in such a way that the distortion that is inherent to the approximation is carefully controlled and known. Distortion correction is commonly applied to calculated bearings and distances to produce values that are a close match to actual field values.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coordinate.ReferenceSystems.TemporalCRSType
files.Summary: The is a 1D coordinate reference system used for the recording of time.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coordinate.ReferenceSystems.VerticalCRSType
files.Summary: The is a 1D coordinate reference system used for recording heights or depths. Vertical CRSs make use of the direction of gravity to define the concept of height or depth, but the relationship with gravity may not be straightforward. By implication, ellipsoidal heights (h) cannot be captured in a vertical coordinate reference system. Ellipsoidal heights cannot exist independently, but only as an inseparable part of a 3D coordinate tuple defined in a geographic 3D coordinate reference system.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coordinate.Systems.AbstractCoordinateSystemType
files.Summary: The is a coordinate system that is the non-repeating sequence of coordinate system axes that spans a given coordinate space. A coordinate system is derived from a set of mathematical rules for specifying how coordinates in a given space are to be assigned to points. The coordinate values in a coordinate tuple shall be recorded in the order in which the coordinate system axes associations are recorded. This abstract complex type shall not be used, extended, or restricted, in an Application Schema, to define a concrete subtype with a meaning equivalent to a concrete subtype specified in this document.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coordinate.Systems.AffineCSType
files.Summary: The is a two- or three-dimensional coordinate system with straight axes that are not necessarily orthogonal. An shall have two or three gml:axis property elements; the number of property elements shall equal the dimension of the coordinate system.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coordinate.Systems.CartesianCSType
files.Summary:
The is a 1-, 2-, or 3-dimensional coordinate system.

  • In the 1-dimensional case, it contains a single straight coordinate axis.
  • In the 2- and 3-dimensional cases gives the position of points relative to orthogonal straight axes. In the multi-dimensional case, all axes shall have the same length unit of measure.
A shall have one, two, or three gml:axis property elements.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coordinate.Systems.CoordinateSystemAxisType
files.Summary: The is a definition of a coordinate system axis.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coordinate.Systems.CylindricalCSType
files.Summary: The is a three-dimensional coordinate system consisting of a polar coordinate system extended by a straight coordinate axis perpendicular to the plane spanned by the polar coordinate system. A shall have three gml:axis property elements.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coordinate.Systems.EllipsoidalCSType
files.Summary: The is a two- or three-dimensional coordinate system in which position is specified by geodetic latitude, geodetic longitude, and (in the three-dimensional case) ellipsoidal height. An shall have two or three gml:axis property elements; the number of associations shall equal the dimension of the CS.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coordinate.Systems.IGeocentricCoordinateSystem
files.Summary: The is used to define coordinate systems that are used in three-dimensional spatial reference frames and are used in earth-centred coordinate systems.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coordinate.Systems.IGeodeticCoordinateSystem
files.Summary: The is used to mark classes that define geodetic coordinate reference systems.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coordinate.Systems.IImageCoordinateSystem
files.Summary: The is used to define planar or grid-based coordinate systems commonly used in engineering or image-related coordinate reference systems.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coordinate.Systems.ITemporalCoordinateSystem
files.Summary: The represents a temporal coordinate system used within a temporal coordinate reference system.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coordinate.Systems.LinearCSType
files.Summary: The is a one-dimensional coordinate system that consists of the points that lie on the single axis described. The associated coordinate is the distance – with or without offset – from the specified datum to the point along the axis. A shall have one gml:axis property element.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coordinate.Systems.ObliqueCartesianCSType
files.Summary: The is a coordinate system that is based on two straight axes that are not necessarily orthogonal.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coordinate.Systems.PolarCSType
files.Summary: The is a two-dimensional coordinate system in which position is specified by the distance from the origin and the angle between the line from the origin to a point and a reference direction. A shall have two gml:axis property elements.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coordinate.Systems.SphericalCSType
files.Summary: The is a three-dimensional coordinate system with one distance measured from the origin and two angular coordinates. A shall have three gml:axis property elements.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coordinate.Systems.TemporalCSType
files.Summary: The is a temporal coordinate system in which time is used as a single axis for positioning.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coordinate.Systems.TimeCSType
files.Summary: The is a one-dimensional coordinate system containing a time axis, used to describe the temporal position of a point in the specified time units from a specified time origin. A shall have one gml:axis property element.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coordinate.Systems.UserDefinedCSType
files.Summary: The is a two- or three-dimensional coordinate system that consists of any combination of coordinate axes not covered by any other coordinate system type. A shall have two or three gml:axis property elements; the number of property elements shall equal the dimension of the coordinate system.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coordinate.Systems.VerticalCSType
files.Summary: The is a one-dimensional coordinate system used to record the heights or depths of points. Such a coordinate system is usually dependent on the Earth's gravity field, perhaps loosely as when atmospheric pressure is the basis for the vertical coordinate system axis. A shall have one gml:axis property element.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coverage.AbstractCoverageType
files.Summary: The base type for coverages is gml:AbstractCoverageType. The basic elements of a coverage can be seen in this content model: the coverage contains gml:domainSet and gml:rangeSet properties. The gml:domainSet property describes the domain of the coverage and the gml:rangeSet property describes the range of the coverage.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coverage.RangeParametersType
files.Summary: gml:RangeParameterType is a framework for the description of the range parameters each of which is a gml:AbstractValue. Specific range parameters are defined through the creation of a GML Application Schema that provides elements that are substitutable for gml:AbstractValue.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Coverage.SequenceRuleType
files.Summary: The gml:SequenceRuleType is derived from the gml:SequenceRuleEnumeration through the addition of an axisOrder attribute. The gml:SequenceRuleEnumeration is an enumerated type. The rule names are defined in ISO 19123. If no rule name is specified the default is “Linear”.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Dictionary.DefinitionBaseType
files.Summary: Represents the base type for definitions in GML. This class serves as a restriction of , implementing the interface.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Dictionary.DefinitionProxyType
files.Summary: Represents a proxy definition that refers to an external definition rather than containing its own definition.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Dictionary.DefinitionType
files.Summary:
The specifies a definition, which can be included in or referenced by a dictionary. The content model for a generic definition is a derivation from .

  • The property shall hold the definition if this can be captured in a simple text string.
  • The property may carry a link to a description elsewhere.
  • The property shall provide one identifier identifying this definition.
  • The property shall be unique within the dictionaries using this definition.
  • The property shall provide zero or more terms and synonyms for which this is the definition.

The property shall be used to hold additional textual information that is not conceptually part of the definition but is useful in understanding the definition.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Dictionary.DictionaryEntryType
files.Summary: A contains or refers to the definitions which are members of a dictionary.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Dictionary.DictionaryType
files.Summary: Sets of definitions may be collected into dictionaries or collections. A is a non-abstract collection of .

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Dictionary.IDictionaryEntry
files.Summary: The allows to define the types that are allowed to be included in .

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Dictionary.IndirectEntryType
files.Summary: Represents an indirect entry in a GML dictionary.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Direction.CompassPointEnumeration
files.Summary: These directions are necessarily approximate, giving direction with a precision of 22.5 degrees. It is thus generally unnecessary to specify the reference frame, though this may be detailed in the definition of a GML application language.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Direction.DirectionDescriptionType
files.Summary: direction descriptions are specified by a compass point code, a keyword, a textual description or a reference to a description. A gml:compassPoint is specified by a simple enumeration. In addition, thre elements to contain text-based descriptions of direction are provided. If the direction is specified using a term from a list, gml:keyword should be used, and the list indicated using the value of the codeSpace attribute. if the direction is decribed in prose, gml:direction or gml:reference should be used, allowing the value to be included inline or by reference.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Direction.DirectionVectorType
files.Summary: Direction vectors are specified by providing components of a vector.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Feature.AbstractFeatureMemberType
files.Summary: To create a collection of GML features, a property type shall be derived by extension from gml:AbstractFeatureMemberType. By default, this abstract property type does not imply any ownership of the features in the collection. The owns attribute of gml:OwnershipAttributeGroup may be used on a property element instance to assert ownership of a feature in the collection. A collection shall not own a feature already owned by another object.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Feature.AbstractFeatureType
files.Summary: The basic feature model is given by the gml:AbstractFeatureType. The content model for gml:AbstractFeatureType adds two specific properties suitable for geographic features to the content model defined in gml:AbstractGMLType. The value of the gml:boundedBy property describes an envelope that encloses the entire feature instance, and is primarily useful for supporting rapid searching for features that occur in a particular location. The value of the gml:location property describes the extent, position or relative location of the feature.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.GenericMetaDataType
files.Summary:
Represents a generic metadata element in GML.

The class allows extensible metadata content in GML. It supports mixed content, meaning it can hold both text and structured XML elements.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Geometry.Aggregates.MultiCurvePropertyType
files.Summary: A property that has a collection of curves as its value domain may either be an appropriate geometry element encapsulated in an element of this type or an XLink reference to a remote geometry element (where remote includes geometry elements located elsewhere in the same document). Either the reference or the contained element shall be given, but neither both nor none.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Geometry.Aggregates.MultiGeometryPropertyType
files.Summary: A property that has a geometric aggregate as its value domain may either be an appropriate geometry element encapsulated in an element of this type or an XLink reference to a remote geometry element (where remote includes geometry elements located elsewhere in the same document). Either the reference or the contained element shall be given, but neither both nor none.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Geometry.Aggregates.MultiPointPropertyType
files.Summary: A property that has a collection of points as its value domain may either be an appropriate geometry element encapsulated in an element of this type or an XLink reference to a remote geometry element (where remote includes geometry elements located elsewhere in the same document). Either the reference or the contained element shall be given, but neither both nor none.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Geometry.Aggregates.MultiSolidPropertyType
files.Summary: A property that has a collection of solids as its value domain may either be an appropriate geometry element encapsulated in an element of this type or an XLink reference to a remote geometry element (where remote includes geometry elements located elsewhere in the same document). Either the reference or the contained element shall be given, but neither both nor none.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Geometry.Aggregates.MultiSurfacePropertyType
files.Summary: A property that has a collection of surfaces as its value domain may either be an appropriate geometry element encapsulated in an element of this type or an XLink reference to a remote geometry element (where remote includes geometry elements located elsewhere in the same document). Either the reference or the contained element shall be given, but neither both nor none.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Geometry.Basic0D1D.AbstractCurveType
files.Summary: gml:AbstractCurveType is an abstraction of a curve to support the different levels of complexity. The curve may always be viewed as a geometric primitive, i.e. is continuous.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Geometry.Basic0D1D.AbstractGeometricPrimitiveType
files.Summary: gml:AbstractGeometricPrimitiveType is the abstract root type of the geometric primitives. A geometric primitive is a geometric object that is not decomposed further into other primitives in the system. All primitives are oriented in the direction implied by the sequence of their coordinate tuples.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Geometry.Basic0D1D.AbstractGeometryType
files.Summary:
All geometry elements are derived directly or indirectly from this abstract supertype. A geometry element may have an identifying attribute (gml:id), one or more names (elements identifier and name) and a description (elements description and descriptionReference) . It may be associated with a spatial reference system (attribute group gml:SRSReferenceGroup).

The following rules shall be adhered to:

  • Every geometry type shall derive from this abstract type.
  • Every geometry element (i.e. an element of a geometry type) shall be directly or indirectly in the substitution group of AbstractGeometry.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Geometry.Basic0D1D.CurveArrayPropertyType
files.Summary: A container for an array of curves. The elements are always contained in the array property, referencing geometry elements or arrays of geometry elements via XLinks is not supported.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Geometry.Basic0D1D.CurvePropertyType
files.Summary: A property that has a curve as its value domain may either be an appropriate geometry element encapsulated in an element of this type or an XLink reference to a remote geometry element (where remote includes geometry elements located elsewhere in the same document). Either the reference or the contained element shall be given, but neither both nor none.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Geometry.Basic0D1D.DirectPositionListType
files.Summary: posList instances (and other instances with the content model specified by DirectPositionListType) hold the coordinates for a sequence of direct positions within the same coordinate reference system (CRS). If no srsName attribute is given, the CRS shall be specified as part of the larger context this geometry element is part of, typically a geometric object like a point, curve, etc. The optional attribute count specifies the number of direct positions in the list. If the attribute count is present then the attribute srsDimension shall be present, too. The number of entries in the list is equal to the product of the dimensionality of the coordinate reference system (i.e. it is a derived value of the coordinate reference system definition) and the number of direct positions.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Geometry.Basic0D1D.DirectPositionType
files.Summary: Direct position instances hold the coordinates for a position within some coordinate reference system (CRS). Since direct positions, as data types, will often be included in larger objects (such as geometry elements) that have references to CRS, the srsName attribute will in general be missing, if this particular direct position is included in a larger element with such a reference to a CRS. In this case, the CRS is implicitly assumed to take on the value of the containing object's CRS. If no srsName attribute is given, the CRS shall be specified as part of the larger context this geometry element is part of, typically a geometric object like a point, curve, etc.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Geometry.Basic0D1D.GeometricPrimitivePropertyType
files.Summary: A property that has a geometric primitive as its value domain may either be an appropriate geometry element encapsulated in an element of this type or an XLink reference to a remote geometry element (where remote includes geometry elements located elsewhere in the same document). Either the reference or the contained element shall be given, but neither both nor none.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Geometry.Basic0D1D.GeometryArrayPropertyType
files.Summary: If a feature has a property which takes an array of geometry elements as its value, this is called a geometry array property. A generic type for such a geometry property is GeometryArrayPropertyType. The elements are always contained inline in the array property, referencing geometry elements or arrays of geometry elements via XLinks is not supported.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Geometry.Basic0D1D.GeometryPropertyType
files.Summary: A geometric property may either be any geometry element encapsulated in an element of this type or an XLink reference to a remote geometry element (where remote includes geometry elements located elsewhere in the same or another document). Note that either the reference or the contained element shall be given, but not both or none. If a feature has a property that takes a geometry element as its value, this is called a geometry property. A generic type for such a geometry property is GeometryPropertyType.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Geometry.Basic0D1D.ISrsInformation
files.Summary: The attributes UomLabels and AxisLabels are optional additional and redundant information for a CRS to simplify the processing of the coordinate values when a more complete definition of the CRS is not needed. This information shall be the same as included in the complete definition of the CRS, referenced by the srsName attribute. When the srsName attribute is included, either both or neither of the axisLabels and uomLabels attributes shall be included. When the srsName attribute is omitted, both of these attributes shall be omitted. The attribute axisLabels is an ordered list of labels for all the axes of this CRS. The gml:axisAbbrev value should be used for these axis labels, after spaces and forbidden characters are removed.When the srsName attribute is included, this attribute is optional.When the srsName attribute is omitted, this attribute shall also be omitted. The attribute uomLabels is an ordered list of unit of measure (uom) labels for all the axes of this CRS.The value of the string in the gml:catalogSymbol should be used for this uom labels, after spaces and forbidden characters are removed. When the axisLabels attribute is included, this attribute shall also be included. When the axisLabels attribute is omitted, this attribute shall also be omitted.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Geometry.Basic0D1D.ISrsReference
files.Summary: The attribute group SRSReferenceGroup is an optional reference to the CRS used by this geometry, with optional additional information to simplify the processing of the coordinates when a more complete definition of the CRS is not needed. In general the attribute srsName points to a CRS instance of gml:AbstractCoordinateReferenceSystem.For well-known references it is not required that the CRS description exists at the location the URI points to. If no srsName attribute is given, the CRS shall be specified as part of the larger context this geometry element is part of.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Geometry.Basic0D1D.PointArrayPropertyType
files.Summary: gml:PointArrayPropertyType is a container for an array of points. The elements are always contained inline in the array property, referencing geometry elements or arrays of geometry elements via XLinks is not supported.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Geometry.Basic0D1D.PointPropertyType
files.Summary: A property that has a point as its value domain may either be an appropriate geometry element encapsulated in an element of this type or an XLink reference to a remote geometry element (where remote includes geometry elements located elsewhere in the same document). Either the reference or the contained element shall be given, but neither both nor none.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Geometry.Basic0D1D.SurfaceInterpolationType
files.Summary: SurfaceInterpolationType is a list of codes that may be used to identify the interpolation mechanisms specified by an application schema.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Geometry.Basic0D1D.VectorType
files.Summary: For some applications the components of the position may be adjusted to yield a unit vector.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Geometry.Basic2D.AbstractRingPropertyType
files.Summary: A property with the content model of gml:AbstractRingPropertyType encapsulates a ring to represent the surface boundary property of a surface.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Geometry.Basic2D.AbstractSurfaceType
files.Summary: gml:AbstractSurfaceType is an abstraction of a surface to support the different levels of complexity. A surface is always a continuous region of a plane.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Geometry.Basic2D.LinearRingPropertyType
files.Summary: A property with the content model of gml:LinearRingPropertyType encapsulates a linear ring to represent a component of a surface boundary.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Geometry.Basic2D.SurfaceArrayPropertyType
files.Summary: gml:SurfaceArrayPropertyType is a container for an array of surfaces. The elements are always contained in the array property, referencing geometry elements or arrays of geometry elements via XLinks is not supported.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Geometry.Basic2D.SurfacePropertyType
files.Summary: A property that has a surface as its value domain may either be an appropriate geometry element encapsulated in an element of this type or an XLink reference to a remote geometry element (where remote includes geometry elements located elsewhere in the same document). Either the reference or the contained element shall be given, but neither both nor none.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Geometry.Complexes.GeometricComplexPropertyType
files.Summary: A property that has a geometric complex as its value domain may either be an appropriate geometry element encapsulated in an element of this type or an XLink reference to a remote geometry element (where remote includes geometry elements located elsewhere in the same document). Either the reference or the contained element shall be given, but neither both nor none.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Geometry.Primitives.AbstractSolidType
files.Summary: gml:AbstractSolidType is an abstraction of a solid to support the different levels of complexity. The solid may always be viewed as a geometric primitive, i.e. is contiguous.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Geometry.Primitives.CurveInterpolationType
files.Summary: gml:CurveInterpolationType is a list of codes that may be used to identify the interpolation mechanisms specified by an application schema.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Geometry.Primitives.CurveSegmentArrayPropertyType
files.Summary: gml:CurveSegmentArrayPropertyType is a container for an array of curve segments.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Geometry.Primitives.KnotPropertyType
files.Summary: gml:KnotPropertyType encapsulates a knot to use it in a geometric type.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Geometry.Primitives.KnotTypesType
files.Summary: This enumeration type specifies values for the knots� type (see ISO 19107:2003, 6.4.25).

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Geometry.Primitives.LineStringSegmentArrayPropertyType
files.Summary: gml:LineStringSegmentArrayPropertyType provides a container for line strings.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Geometry.Primitives.PolygonPatchArrayPropertyType
files.Summary: gml:PolygonPatchArrayPropertyType provides a container for an array of polygon patches.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Geometry.Primitives.RingPropertyType
files.Summary: A property with the content model of gml:RingPropertyType encapsulates a ring to represent a component of a surface boundary.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Geometry.Primitives.ShellPropertyType
files.Summary: A property with the content model of gml:ShellPropertyType encapsulates a shell to represent a component of a solid boundary.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Geometry.Primitives.SolidArrayPropertyType
files.Summary: gml:SolidArrayPropertyType is a container for an array of solids. The elements are always contained in the array property, referencing geometry elements or arrays of geometry elements is not supported.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Geometry.Primitives.SolidPropertyType
files.Summary: A property that has a solid as its value domain may either be an appropriate geometry element encapsulated in an element of this type or an XLink reference to a remote geometry element (where remote includes geometry elements located elsewhere in the same document). Either the reference or the contained element shall be given, but neither both nor none.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Geometry.Primitives.SurfacePatchArrayPropertyType
files.Summary: gml:SurfacePatchArrayPropertyType is a container for a sequence of surface patches.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Geometry.Primitives.TrianglePatchArrayPropertyType
files.Summary: gml:TrianglePatchArrayPropertyType provides a container for an array of triangle patches.

files.Summary:

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Temporal.TimePositionType
files.Summary:
The method for identifying a temporal position is specific to each temporal reference system. TimePositionType supports the description of temporal position according to the subtypes described in ISO 19108. Values based on calendars and clocks use lexical formats that are based on ISO 8601, as described in XML Schema Part 2:2001. A decimal value may be used with coordinate systems such as GPS time or UNIX time. A URI may be used to provide a reference to some era in an ordinal reference system. In common with many of the components modelled as data types in the ISO 19100 series of International Standards, the corresponding GML component has simple content. However, the content model TimePositionType is defined in several steps. Three XML attributes appear on TimePositionType:
A time value shall be associated with a temporal reference system through the frame attribute that provides a URI reference that identifies a description of the reference system. Following ISO 19108, the Gregorian calendar with UTC is the default reference system, but others may also be used. Components for describing temporal reference systems are described in 14.4, but it is not required that the reference system be described in this, as the reference may refer to anything that may be identified with a URI. For time values using a calendar containing more than one era, the (optional) calendarEraName attribute provides the name of the calendar era. Inexact temporal positions may be expressed using the optional indeterminatePosition attribute. This takes a value from an enumeration.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Gml.Units.ConversionToPreferredUnitType
files.Summary:
The inherited attribute uom references the preferred unit that this conversion applies to. The conversion of a unit to the preferred unit for this physical quantity type is specified by an arithmetic conversion (scaling and/or offset). The content model extends gml:UnitOfMeasureType, which has a mandatory attribute uom which identifies the preferred unit for the physical quantity type that this conversion applies to. The conversion is specified by a choice of

  • gml:factor, which defines the scale factor, or
  • gml:formula, which defines a formula by which a value using the conventional unit of measure can be converted to obtain the corresponding value using the preferred unit of measure. The formula defines the parameters of a simple formula by which a value using the conventional unit of measure can be converted to the corresponding value using the preferred unit of measure. The formula element contains elements a, b, c and d, whose values use the XML Schema type double. These values are used in the formula y = (a + bx) / (c + dx), where x is a value using this unit, and y is the corresponding value using the base unit. The elements a and d are optional, and if values are not provided, those parameters are considered to be zero. If values are not provided for both a and d, the formula is equivalent to a fraction with numerator and denominator parameters.

The value of the gml:boundedBy property describes an envelope that encloses the entire feature instance, and is primarily useful for supporting rapid searching for features that occur in a particular location. The value of the gml:location property describes the extent, position or relative location of the feature.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Metadata.AbstractGeometryType
files.Summary:

A geometry element may have an identifying attribute (gml:id), one or more names (elements identifier and name) and a description (elements description and descriptionReference) . It may be associated with a spatial reference system (attribute group gml:SRSReferenceGroup). The following rules shall be adhered to:

  • Every geometry type shall derive from this abstract type.
  • Every geometry element (i.e. an element of a geometry type) shall be directly or indirectly in the substitution group of AbstractGeometry.

By default, this abstract property type does not imply any ownership of the objects in the collection. The owns attribute of gml:OwnershipAttributeGroup may be used on a property element instance to assert ownership of an object in the collection. A collection shall not own an object already owned by another object.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Metadata.AbstractMetadataPropertyType

The value of such a property shall be metadata. The content model of such a property type, i.e. the metadata application schema shall be specified by the GML Application Schema. By default, this abstract property type does not imply any ownership of the metadata. The owns attribute of gml:OwnershipAttributeGroup may be used on a metadata property element instance to assert ownership of the metadata. If metadata following the conceptual model of ISO 19115 is to be encoded in a GML document, the corresponding Implementation Specification specified in ISO/TS 19139 shall be used to encode the metadata information.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Metadata.ConcatenatedOperationType
files.Summary: gml:ConcatenatedOperation is an ordered sequence of two or more coordinate operations. This sequence of operations is constrained by the requirement that the source coordinate reference system of step (n+1) must be the same as the target coordinate reference system of step (n). The source coordinate reference system of the first step and the target coordinate reference system of the last step are the source and target coordinate reference system associated with the concatenated operation. Instead of a forward operation, an inverse operation may be used for one or more of the operation steps mentioned above, if the inverse operation is uniquely defined by the forward operation. The gml:coordOperation property elements are an ordered sequence of associations to the two or more operations used by this concatenated operation. The AggregationAttributeGroup should be used to specify that the coordOperation associations are ordered.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Metadata.ConversionToPreferredUnitType
files.Summary:
The inherited attribute uom references the preferred unit that this conversion applies to. The conversion of a unit to the preferred unit for this physical quantity type is specified by an arithmetic conversion (scaling and/or offset). The content model extends gml:UnitOfMeasureType, which has a mandatory attribute uom which identifies the preferred unit for the physical quantity type that this conversion applies to. The conversion is specified by a choice of

  • gml:factor, which defines the scale factor, or
  • gml:formula, which defines a formula by which a value using the conventional unit of measure can be converted to obtain the corresponding value using the preferred unit of measure. The formula defines the parameters of a simple formula by which a value using the conventional unit of measure can be converted to the corresponding value using the preferred unit of measure. The formula element contains elements a, b, c and d, whose values use the XML Schema type double. These values are used in the formula y = (a + bx) / (c + dx), where x is a value using this unit, and y is the corresponding value using the base unit. The elements a and d are optional, and if values are not provided, those parameters are considered to be zero. If values are not provided for both a and d, the formula is equivalent to a fraction with numerator and denominator parameters.

These attributes are deprecated. The attributes were intended to be used as follows: Decimal symbol used for a decimal point (default=”.” a stop or period) cs symbol used to separate components within a tuple or coordinate string (default=”,” a comma) ts symbol used to separate tuples or coordinate strings (default=” “ a space) Since it is based on the XML Schema string type, CoordinatesType may be used in the construction of tables of tuples or arrays of tuples, including ones that contain mixed text and numeric values.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Metadata.DirectPositionListType
files.Summary: posList instances (and other instances with the content model specified by DirectPositionListType) hold the coordinates for a sequence of direct positions within the same coordinate reference system (CRS). if no srsName attribute is given, the CRS shall be specified as part of the larger context this geometry element is part of, typically a geometric object like a point, curve, etc. The optional attribute count specifies the number of direct positions in the list. If the attribute count is present then the attribute srsDimension shall be present, too. The number of entries in the list is equal to the product of the dimensionality of the coordinate reference system (i.e. it is a derived value of the coordinate reference system definition) and the number of direct positions.

files.Summary: Direct position instances hold the coordinates for a position within some coordinate reference system (CRS). Since direct positions, as data types, will often be included in larger objects (such as geometry elements) that have references to CRS, the srsName attribute will in general be missing, if this particular direct position is included in a larger element with such a reference to a CRS. In this case, the CRS is implicitly assumed to take on the value of the containing object's CRS. if no srsName attribute is given, the CRS shall be specified as part of the larger context this geometry element is part of, typically a geometric object like a point, curve, etc.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Metadata.IdentifiedObjectType
files.Summary: gml:IdentifiedObjectType provides identification properties of a CRS-related object. In gml:DefinitionType, the gml:identifier element shall be the primary name by which this object is identified, encoding the "name" attribute in the UML model. Zero or more of the gml:name elements can be an unordered set of "identifiers", encoding the "identifier" attribute in the UML model. Each of these gml:name elements can reference elsewhere the object's defining information or be an identifier by which this object can be referenced. Zero or more other gml:name elements can be an unordered set of "alias" alternative names by which this CRS related object is identified, encoding the "alias" attributes in the UML model. An object may have several aliases, typically used in different contexts. The context for an alias is indicated by the value of its (optional) codeSpace attribute. Any needed version information shall be included in the codeSpace attribute of a gml:identifier and gml:name elements. In this use, the gml:remarks element in the gml:DefinitionType shall contain comments on or information about this object, including data source information.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Metadata.SecondDefiningParameter
files.Summary: gml:secondDefiningParameter is a property containing the definition of the second parameter that defines the shape of an ellipsoid. An ellipsoid requires two defining parameters: semi-major axis and inverse flattening or semi-major axis and semi-minor axis. When the reference body is a sphere rather than an ellipsoid, only a single defining parameter is required, namely the radius of the sphere; in that case, the semi-major axis "degenerates" into the radius of the sphere. The inverseFlattening element contains the inverse flattening value of the ellipsoid. This value is a scale factor (or ratio). It uses gml:LengthType with the restriction that the unit of measure referenced by the uom attribute must be suitable for a scale factor, such as percent, permil, or parts-per-million. The semiMinorAxis element contains the length of the semi-minor axis of the ellipsoid. When the isSphere element is included, the ellipsoid is degenerate and is actually a sphere. The sphere is completely defined by the semi-major axis, which is the radius of the sphere.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Metadata.TimePositionType
files.Summary: The method for identifying a temporal position is specific to each temporal reference system. gml:TimePositionType supports the description of temporal position according to the subtypes described in ISO 19108. Values based on calendars and clocks use lexical formats that are based on ISO 8601, as described in XML Schema Part 2:2001. A decimal value may be used with coordinate systems such as GPS time or UNIX time. A URI may be used to provide a reference to some era in an ordinal reference system . In common with many of the components modelled as data types in the ISO 19100 series of International Standards, the corresponding GML component has simple content. However, the content model gml:TimePositionType is defined in several steps. Three XML attributes appear on gml:TimePositionType: A time value shall be associated with a temporal reference system through the frame attribute that provides a URI reference that identifies a description of the reference system. Following ISO 19108, the Gregorian calendar with UTC is the default reference system, but others may also be used. Components for describing temporal reference systems are described in 14.4, but it is not required that the reference system be described in this, as the reference may refer to anything that may be indentified with a URI. For time values using a calendar containing more than one era, the (optional) calendarEraName attribute provides the name of the calendar era. Inexact temporal positions may be expressed using the optional indeterminatePosition attribute. This takes a value from an enumeration.

files.Summary: Represents a standardized way to document the reason for a missing or null value in geospatial metadata. It is based on the gml:NilReasonType definition in the GML schema and supports enumerated reasons as well as custom user-defined explanations. The class ensures that nil reasons are properly structured, validated, and serialized for interoperability with XML and JSON-based metadata systems.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Metadata.V2003.Common.ObjectReference_PropertyType

It provides attributes that define relationships between metadata elements, enabling linkage to remote resources via unique identifiers or hyperlinks. This class incorporates elements from the XLink standard (xlink) and supports referencing via attributes such as href, role, arcrole, and title. Additionally, it implements mechanisms for specifying missing values through the nilReason attribute, following the gml:NilReasonType convention.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Metadata.V2003.Gml.Base.AbstractMetadataPropertyType
files.Summary: To associate metadata described by any XML Schema with a GML object, a property element shall be defined whose content model is derived by extension from gml:AbstractMetadataPropertyType. The value of such a property shall be metadata. The content model of such a property type, i.e. the metadata application schema shall be specified by the GML Application Schema. By default, this abstract property type does not imply any ownership of the metadata. The owns attribute of gml:OwnershipAttributeGroup may be used on a metadata property element instance to assert ownership of the metadata. If metadata following the conceptual model of ISO 19115 is to be encoded in a GML document, the corresponding Implementation Specification specified in ISO/TS 19139 shall be used to encode the metadata information.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Metadata.V2003.Gml.Base.Association
files.Summary: Represents a generalized association in GML, providing an XLink-based mechanism for referencing external or internal resources within geospatial metadata. This abstract class implements the GML AssociationAttributeGroup pattern from gmlBase.xsd, enabling a standard approach for linking GML objects and facilitating interoperability with ISO 19115:2003 metadata structures.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Metadata.V2003.Gml.Base.IOwnershipAttributeGroup
files.Summary: Encoding a GML property inline vs. by-reference shall not imply anything about the “ownership” of the contained or referenced GML Object, i.e.the encoding style shall not imply any “deep-copy” or “deep-delete” semantics.To express ownership over the contained or referenced GML Object, the gml:OwnershipAttributeGroup attribute group may be added to object-valued property elements.If the attribute group is not part of the content model of such a property element, then the value may not be “owned”. When the value of the owns attribute is "true", the existence of inline or referenced object(s) depends upon the existence of the parent object.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Metadata.V2003.Gml.BasicTypes.CoordinatesType
files.Summary: This type is deprecated for tuples with ordinate values that are numbers. CoordinatesType is a text string, intended to be used to record an array of tuples or coordinates. While it is not possible to enforce the internal structure of the string through schema validation, some optional attributes have been provided in previous versions of GML to support a description of the internal structure. These attributes are deprecated. The attributes were intended to be used as follows: Decimal symbol used for a decimal point (default=”.” a stop or period) cs symbol used to separate components within a tuple or coordinate string (default=”,” a comma) ts symbol used to separate tuples or coordinate strings (default=” “ a space) Since it is based on the XML Schema string type, CoordinatesType may be used in the construction of tables of tuples or arrays of tuples, including ones that contain mixed text and numeric values.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Metadata.V2003.Gml.Coordinate.Datums.SecondDefiningParameter
files.Summary: SecondDefiningParameter is a property containing the definition of the second parameter that defines the shape of an ellipsoid. An ellipsoid requires two defining parameters: semi-major axis and inverse flattening or semi-major axis and semi-minor axis. When the reference body is a sphere rather than an ellipsoid, only a single defining parameter is required, namely the radius of the sphere; in that case, the semi-major axis "degenerates" into the radius of the sphere. The inverseFlattening element contains the inverse flattening value of the ellipsoid. This value is a scale factor (or ratio). It uses gml:LengthType with the restriction that the unit of measure referenced by the uom attribute must be suitable for a scale factor, such as percent, permil, or parts-per-million. The semiMinorAxis element contains the length of the semi-minor axis of the ellipsoid. When the isSphere element is included, the ellipsoid is degenerate and is actually a sphere. The sphere is completely defined by the semi-major axis, which is the radius of the sphere.

The inverseFlattening element contains the inverse flattening value of the ellipsoid. This value is a scale factor (or ratio). It uses withthe restriction that the unit of measure referenced by the uom attribute must be suitable for a scale factor, such as percent, permil, or parts-per-million. The semiMinorAxis element contains the length of the semi-minor axis of the ellipsoid. When the isSphere element is included, the ellipsoid is degenerate and is actually a sphere. files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Metadata.V2003.Gml.Coordinate.Operations.ConcatenatedOperationType
files.Summary: gml:ConcatenatedOperation is an ordered sequence of two or more coordinate operations. This sequence of operations is constrained by the requirement that the source coordinate reference system of step (n+1) must be the same as the target coordinate reference system of step (n). The source coordinate reference system of the first step and the target coordinate reference system of the last step are the source and target coordinate reference system associated with the concatenated operation. Instead of a forward operation, an inverse operation may be used for one or more of the operation steps mentioned above, if the inverse operation is uniquely defined by the forward operation. The gml:coordOperation property elements are an ordered sequence of associations to the two or more operations used by this concatenated operation. The AggregationAttributeGroup should be used to specify that the coordOperation associations are ordered.

files.Summary: IdentifiedObjectType provides identification properties of a CRS-related object. In DefinitionType, the gml:identifier element shall be the primary name by which this object is identified, encoding the "name" attribute in the UML model. Zero or more of the gml:name elements can be an unordered set of "identifiers", encoding the "identifier" attribute in the UML model. Each of these gml:name elements can reference elsewhere the object's defining information or be an identifier by which this object can be referenced. Zero or more other gml:name elements can be an unordered set of "alias" alternative names by which this CRS related object is identified, encoding the "alias" attributes in the UML model. An object may have several aliases, typically used in different contexts. The context for an alias is indicated by the value of its (optional) codeSpace attribute. In this use, the gml:remarks element in the gml:DefinitionType shall contain comments on or information about this object, including data source information.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Metadata.V2003.Gml.Temporal.TimePositionType
files.Summary:
The method for identifying a temporal position is specific to each temporal reference system. TimePositionType supports the description of temporal position according to the subtypes described in ISO 19108. Values based on calendars and clocks use lexical formats that are based on ISO 8601, as described in XML Schema Part 2:2001. A decimal value may be used with coordinate systems such as GPS time or UNIX time. A URI may be used to provide a reference to some era in an ordinal reference system. In common with many of the components modelled as data types in the ISO 19100 series of International Standards, the corresponding GML component has simple content. However, the content model TimePositionType is defined in several steps. Three XML attributes appear on TimePositionType:
A time value shall be associated with a temporal reference system through the frame attribute that provides a URI reference that identifies a description of the reference system. Following ISO 19108, the Gregorian calendar with UTC is the default reference system, but others may also be used. Components for describing temporal reference systems are described in 14.4, but it is not required that the reference system be described in this, as the reference may refer to anything that may be indentified with a URI. For time values using a calendar containing more than one era, the (optional) calendarEraName attribute provides the name of the calendar era. Inexact temporal positions may be expressed using the optional indeterminatePosition attribute. This takes a value from an enumeration.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Metadata.V2003.Gml.Units.ConversionToPreferredUnitType
files.Summary:
The inherited attribute uom references the preferred unit that this conversion applies to. The conversion of a unit to the preferred unit for this physical quantity type is specified by an arithmetic conversion (scaling and/or offset). The content model extends gml:UnitOfMeasureType, which has a mandatory attribute uom which identifies the preferred unit for the physical quantity type that this conversion applies to. The conversion is specified by a choice of

  • gml:factor, which defines the scale factor, or
  • gml:formula, which defines a formula by which a value using the conventional unit of measure can be converted to obtain the corresponding value using the preferred unit of measure. The formula defines the parameters of a simple formula by which a value using the conventional unit of measure can be converted to the corresponding value using the preferred unit of measure. The formula element contains elements a, b, c and d, whose values use the XML Schema type double. These values are used in the formula y = (a + bx) / (c + dx), where x is a value using this unit, and y is the corresponding value using the base unit. The elements a and d are optional, and if values are not provided, those parameters are considered to be zero. If values are not provided for both a and d, the formula is equivalent to a fraction with numerator and denominator parameters.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Metadata.V2003.Thin.GML.Base.AbstractMetadataPropertyType
files.Summary: To associate metadata described by any XML Schema with a GML object, a property element shall be defined whose content model is derived by extension from gml:AbstractMetadataPropertyType. The value of such a property shall be metadata. The content model of such a property type, i.e. the metadata application schema shall be specified by the GML Application Schema. By default, this abstract property type does not imply any ownership of the metadata. The owns attribute of gml:OwnershipAttributeGroup may be used on a metadata property element instance to assert ownership of the metadata. If metadata following the conceptual model of ISO 19115 is to be encoded in a GML document, the corresponding Implementation Specification specified in ISO/TS 19139 shall be used to encode the metadata information.

When the value of the owns attribute is "true", the existence of inline or referenced object(s) depends upon the existence of the parent object.

The attributes were intended to be used as follows: Decimal symbol used for a decimal point (default=”.” a stop or period) cs symbol used to separate components within a tuple or coordinate string (default=”,” a comma) ts symbol used to separate tuples or coordinate strings (default=” “ a space) Since it is based on the XML Schema string type, CoordinatesType may be used in the construction of tables of tuples or arrays of tuples, including ones that contain mixed text and numeric values.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Metadata.V2003.Thin.GML.Coordinate.Datums.SecondDefiningParameter
files.Summary: SecondDefiningParameter is a property containing the definition of the second parameter that defines the shape of an ellipsoid. An ellipsoid requires two defining parameters: semi-major axis and inverse flattening or semi-major axis and semi-minor axis. When the reference body is a sphere rather than an ellipsoid, only a single defining parameter is required, namely the radius of the sphere; in that case, the semi-major axis "degenerates" into the radius of the sphere. The inverseFlattening element contains the inverse flattening value of the ellipsoid. This value is a scale factor (or ratio). It uses gml:LengthType with the restriction that the unit of measure referenced by the uom attribute must be suitable for a scale factor, such as percent, permil, or parts-per-million. The semiMinorAxis element contains the length of the semi-minor axis of the ellipsoid. When the isSphere element is included, the ellipsoid is degenerate and is actually a sphere. The sphere is completely defined by the semi-major axis, which is the radius of the sphere.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Metadata.V2003.Thin.GML.Coordinate.Operations.ConcatenatedOperationType
files.Summary: gml:ConcatenatedOperation is an ordered sequence of two or more coordinate operations. This sequence of operations is constrained by the requirement that the source coordinate reference system of step (n+1) must be the same as the target coordinate reference system of step (n). The source coordinate reference system of the first step and the target coordinate reference system of the last step are the source and target coordinate reference system associated with the concatenated operation. Instead of a forward operation, an inverse operation may be used for one or more of the operation steps mentioned above, if the inverse operation is uniquely defined by the forward operation. The gml:coordOperation property elements are an ordered sequence of associations to the two or more operations used by this concatenated operation. The AggregationAttributeGroup should be used to specify that the coordOperation associations are ordered.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Metadata.V2003.Thin.GML.Temporal.TimePositionType
files.Summary:
The method for identifying a temporal position is specific to each temporal reference system. TimePositionType supports the description of temporal position according to the subtypes described in ISO 19108. Values based on calendars and clocks use lexical formats that are based on ISO 8601, as described in XML Schema Part 2:2001. A decimal value may be used with coordinate systems such as GPS time or UNIX time. A URI may be used to provide a reference to some era in an ordinal reference system. In common with many of the components modelled as data types in the ISO 19100 series of International Standards, the corresponding GML component has simple content. However, the content model TimePositionType is defined in several steps. Three XML attributes appear on TimePositionType:
A time value shall be associated with a temporal reference system through the frame attribute that provides a URI reference that identifies a description of the reference system. Following ISO 19108, the Gregorian calendar with UTC is the default reference system, but others may also be used. Components for describing temporal reference systems are described in 14.4, but it is not required that the reference system be described in this, as the reference may refer to anything that may be indentified with a URI. For time values using a calendar containing more than one era, the (optional) calendarEraName attribute provides the name of the calendar era. Inexact temporal positions may be expressed using the optional indeterminatePosition attribute. This takes a value from an enumeration.

files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Metadata.V2003.Thin.GML.Units.ConversionToPreferredUnitType
files.Summary:
The inherited attribute uom references the preferred unit that this conversion applies to. The conversion of a unit to the preferred unit for this physical quantity type is specified by an arithmetic conversion (scaling and/or offset). The content model extends gml:UnitOfMeasureType, which has a mandatory attribute uom which identifies the preferred unit for the physical quantity type that this conversion applies to. The conversion is specified by a choice of

  • gml:factor, which defines the scale factor, or
  • gml:formula, which defines a formula by which a value using the conventional unit of measure can be converted to obtain the corresponding value using the preferred unit of measure. The formula defines the parameters of a simple formula by which a value using the conventional unit of measure can be converted to the corresponding value using the preferred unit of measure. The formula element contains elements a, b, c and d, whose values use the XML Schema type double. These values are used in the formula y = (a + bx) / (c + dx), where x is a value using this unit, and y is the corresponding value using the base unit. The elements a and d are optional, and if values are not provided, those parameters are considered to be zero. If values are not provided for both a and d, the formula is equivalent to a fraction with numerator and denominator parameters.

That object contains an estimate of the impact of this coordinate operation on point accuracy. files.Title: NDSH.Geospatial.Metadata.secondDefiningParameter
files.Summary: gml:secondDefiningParameter is a property containing the definition of the second parameter that defines the shape of an ellipsoid. An ellipsoid requires two defining parameters: semi-major axis and inverse flattening or semi-major axis and semi-minor axis. When the reference body is a sphere rather than an ellipsoid, only a single defining parameter is required, namely the radius of the sphere; in that case, the semi-major axis "degenerates" into the radius of the sphere. The inverseFlattening element contains the inverse flattening value of the ellipsoid. This value is a scale factor (or ratio). It uses gml:LengthType with the restriction that the unit of measure referenced by the uom attribute must be suitable for a scale factor, such as percent, permil, or parts-per-million. The semiMinorAxis element contains the length of the semi-minor axis of the ellipsoid. When the isSphere element is included, the ellipsoid is degenerate and is actually a sphere. The sphere is completely defined by the semi-major axis, which is the radius of the sphere.
